description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/link/lichen_link_rx.c
Lines: 287-291

authenticate_inner_payload() ignores return values from tinycrypt SHA256 functions when deriving src_eui64 from peer_pubkey:

```c
} else if (ctx->peer_pubkey != NULL) {
    struct tc_sha256_state_struct sha_state;
    uint8_t hash[TC_SHA256_DIGEST_SIZE];

    (void)tc_sha256_init(&sha_state);        // Return value ignored
    (void)tc_sha256_update(&sha_state, ctx->peer_pubkey,
                           SCHNORR48_PUBKEY_LEN);  // Return value ignored
    (void)tc_sha256_final(hash, &sha_state); // Return value ignored
    memcpy(src_eui64, hash, LICHEN_EUI64_LEN);
}
```

tc_sha256_update and tc_sha256_final return TC_CRYPTO_FAIL (0) on NULL parameters. While the parameters are validated earlier making failure unlikely, ignoring crypto function return values is not defensive programming.

Impact: If hash computation fails (currently unlikely), src_eui64 would contain uninitialized/garbage data, potentially causing incorrect sender identification.

Fix: Check return values and propagate errors, or add static assert that the tinycrypt functions cannot fail given non-NULL inputs.
